## IFC as a Novel, Drawings as the Script, and Construction as the Play
A different way to think about how information becomes action

IFC is often described with technical metaphors — schemas, databases, containers, languages. They’re fine, but they don’t quite capture the shape of the thing. Another way to think about IFC is as a novel: a complete narrative world containing every character, relationship, and structural rule. It’s rich, internally coherent, and deliberately comprehensive. But like a novel, it isn’t something you hand to the people who need to perform it.

To make a novel performable, you create a script.
In construction, those are the drawings.

Drawings are a selective adaptation of the IFC world. They strip away what isn’t load‑bearing for the task at hand and present only what needs to be enacted. They’re not the whole story; they’re the operational slice of it.

But even a script isn’t enough to run a play.
Theatre relies on something else: the script breakdown.

A script breakdown is where the stage manager reads the script with a pencil and extracts everything that must happen for the performance to work — entrances, exits, props, cues, set changes, timing, dependencies. It’s the bridge between narrative and logistics.

Construction has the same moment, and it doesn’t happen in the design office.
It happens when the contractor takes the drawings and turns them into something performable.

This is the contractor’s equivalent of the script breakdown:

lift drawings

shop drawings

fabrication details

temporary works plans

site logistics diagrams

work packages

short‑interval schedules

TAKT plans

This is where the contractor stops reading drawings as abstractions and starts reading them as tasks. It’s the point where the building becomes something that can be enacted reliably, safely, and in the right order.

TAKT planning fits naturally here.
CPM gives you a theoretical model of time; TAKT gives you a practical model of work. CPM is the literary analysis; TAKT is the cue sheet. It tells you who moves when, in what space, with what hand‑offs, and at what rhythm. It’s the choreography of the performance.

By the time construction begins, the analogy is complete:

IFC is the novel — the full world.

Drawings are the script — the adaptation.

Contractor’s breakdown is the stage manager’s breakdown — the logistics.

TAKT planning is the cue sheet — the temporal choreography.

Construction is the play — the world performed into reality.

Nothing dramatic. No evangelism. Just another way to describe how information becomes instruction, and how a building moves from narrative to performance.
